Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Cut @Fingerling Potatoes{12%ounce} in half lengthwise. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @Shallot{1}.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @Vegetable Oil{drizzle}, @Dried Thyme{1%tsp}, and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Roast in oven until tender and crisped, ~{20-25%minutes} total (we'll be adding more items to the sheet after 10 minutes).

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Season @Pork Tenderloin{12%ounce} all over with salt and pepper. Add to pan and cook, turning occasionally, until browned all over, ~{6-8%minutes}. Transfer to another baking sheet and let roast in oven to desired doneness, ~{8-12%minutes}.

While pork cooks, toss @Broccoli Florets{8%ounce} in a #medium bowl{} with a drizzle of oil and a pinch of salt and pepper. Remove potatoes from oven after they have roasted 10 minutes. Give them a toss and push toward one side of sheet. Spread broccoli on other side of sheet. Return to oven and roast until potatoes are done and broccoli is tender and lightly crisped, ~{12-15%minutes} more.

Lower heat under pan used for pork to medium and add shallot and a drizzle of oil. Cook, tossing, until lightly browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Pour in @Balsamic Vinegar{5%tsp} and let simmer until reduced by half. Stir in @Cherry Preserves{1%tbsp} and @water{1%tbsp}. Season with salt, pepper, and up to @Sugar{1/2%tsp} (you may use less to taste). Remove pan from heat and add @Butter{1%tbsp}, stirring to melt.

After pork is done roasting, return pan to medium heat. Add pork and turn to coat in glaze. Hold pork over pan, letting excess glaze drip off, then transfer to a #cutting board{}. Let rest ~{1-2%minutes}, then slice. Divide between plates and drizzle with remaining glaze in pan. Serve with broccoli and potatoes.

> This week’s HelloFresh Hall of Fame recipe is part sweet, part tangy, and all-around delicious, thanks to the jammy, flavorful, stick-to-your-spoon-thick cherry balsamic glaze that our happy cooks absolutely loved the last time we made this recipe. The sides are kept simple, with roasted broccoli and potatoes that allow the pan-seared pork tenderloin to shine. And boy, does it steal the show.